I want to build a AI tool which should be able to predict landuse of a geocoded piont in india.
ChatGPT said:

Summary view: you want an AI that takes a geocoded point (lat, lon in India) and returns its land-use class. below I make assumptions, challenge design choices you might make, then give a concrete, actionable pipeline with options, data sources, modeling choices, evaluation plan, deployment architecture, and an immediate step-by-step work plan you can execute now.

ASSUMPTIONS

  • Input: single geocoded point (lat, lon).

  • Output: one land-use label (e.g., residential, agriculture, industrial, commercial, water, forest, barren, transportation, mixed).

  • Scale: national (India) ‚Äî large geographic/heterogeneous data.

  • You have basic Python knowledge and can run tools (GDAL/rasterio, geopandas, PyTorch/TF, scikit-learn).
    If any assumption is wrong, the plan still adapts ‚Äî I‚Äôll propose alternatives below.

KEY DESIGN DECISIONS (and questions you should mentally answer)

  1. Label taxonomy: how many classes? (coarse 6‚Äì8 classes easier; fine-grained 15+ harder and needs more labeled data).
    ‚Äî Recommendation: start with 8 classes (residential, commercial, industrial, agriculture, forest, water, barren/other, transportation).

  2. Spatial context: point-only vs. patch context? Land-use usually needs context (100‚Äì500 m patch). Use image patch around point rather than single pixel.

  3. Label source: will you rely on existing maps (OSM, government cadastral, NLUD) for labels or annotate manually/crowdsource? Existing maps scale fastest but contain errors.

  4. Temporal sensitivity: are seasonal changes important? (agriculture varies seasonally) ‚Äî include multi-temporal imagery if yes.

  5. Real-time vs batch: do you need low-latency API for single-point queries? (affects deployment choice)

DATA SOURCES (what to use and why)

  • Satellite imagery (primary features): Sentinel-2 (10‚Äì20 m, multispectral, free), Landsat 8/9 (30 m), PlanetScope (paid, 3‚Äì5 m) if you need high-res. Use Sentinel-2 as baseline.

  • Vector data for labels / features: OpenStreetMap (buildings, landuse polygons, roads, POIs), Indian government datasets (NLUD ‚Äî National Land Use Database / state cadastral portals), ISRO Bhuvan layers (where accessible).

  • Ancillary raster layers: Digital Elevation Model (SRTM), night-time lights (VIIRS), population density (WorldPop/HRSL), road density (from OSM).

  • Ground truth: manual annotation, OpenStreetMap tags, or datasets from research (if available). Start by deriving labels from OSM + NLUD with manual validation.

FEATURE ENGINEERING (practical)

  • Image patch (e.g., 256√ó256 px at 10 m ‚Üí 2.56 km¬≤) centered on point ‚Äî tune size.

  • Spectral bands: use RGB + NIR + SWIR if available (Sentinel-2 bands 2,3,4,8,11) or compute NDVI, NDWI, NDBI.

  • Temporal features: median/percentile composites across seasons; seasonal NDVI amplitude.

  • Contextual vector features: distance to nearest road, building density, POI counts, OSM landuse polygon category overlap, elevation, slope.

  • Categorical encoding: one-hot encode OSM derived tags (e.g., highway type near point).

MODELING APPROACHES (three practical options)

  1. Patch-based CNN classifier (recommended start)

    • Input: multispectral image patch (and optionally stacked ancillary rasters).

    • Model: lightweight CNN (EfficientNet/ResNet backbone) or custom CNN; for multispectral add first conv match channels.

    • Pros: learns spatial patterns; scales well.

    • Cons: needs labeled patches and GPU for training.

  2. Tabular/ensemble model

    • Input: engineered features (NDVI, distances, POI counts, DEM stats).

    • Model: XGBoost / RandomForest.

    • Pros: easier to train, interpretable, smaller data needs.

    • Cons: misses rich spatial patterns.

  3. Hybrid (best long-term)

    • Train CNN for image features, extract penultimate layer embeddings, combine with tabular features in XGBoost or MLP.

LABELING STRATEGIES

  • Automatic labeling via polygon overlays: assign label of the polygon (NLUD/OSM) that contains the point. Validate a sample to estimate label noise.

  • Active learning loop: train initial model on noisy labels, surface uncertain predictions for human correction.

  • Crowdsourcing: use a small annotation UI (labelbox, CVAT, custom) for edge cases.

  • Class balance: oversample underrepresented classes, use focal loss or class-weighting.

EVALUATION METRICS & VALIDATION

  • Primary: overall accuracy, class-wise F1, confusion matrix (watch agriculture vs fallow vs barren).

  • Spatial cross-validation: split by geographic regions (train on some states, test on others) to evaluate generalization.

  • Temporal holdout: train on one year, test on another if multi-temporal features used.

PIPELINE (concrete components & tools)

  1. Data collection

    • Download Sentinel-2 tiles for India (use Google Earth Engine or sentinelhub-py).

    • Download OSM extracts for India (e.g., Geofabrik) and state NLUD if available.

  2. Preprocessing

    • Reproject to common CRS, resample bands, compute indices (NDVI/NDWI).

    • Build point dataset: for each labeled point, extract image patch and tabular features.

  3. Training

    • Data augmentations: flips, small rotations, brightness jitter, spectral noise.

    • Use PyTorch Lightning or standard PyTorch to train CNN; use sklearn/XGBoost for tabular.

  4. Evaluation

    • Geographic cross-validation, confusion matrices, per-class reports.

  5. Deployment

    • Model server: FastAPI + TorchServe or ONNX model for low latency.

    • Spatial DB: PostGIS to store polygons/metadata.

    • API flow: API receives lat/lon ‚Üí extracts/requests required imagery/patch (or uses precomputed tiles) ‚Üí model inference ‚Üí return label + confidence + explanation (saliency/nearest training samples).

  6. Monitoring

    • Track accuracy drift by sampling predictions and comparing to updated ground truth.

RISKS & MITIGATIONS

  • Noisy labels (OSM inaccuracies): mitigate with active learning and manual validation.

  • Class imbalance: use sampling strategies and appropriate loss functions.

  • Seasonal variability (agriculture): include multi-temporal features.

  • Legal/privacy/usage: check data licensing for commercial use (OSM = ODbL; Sentinel = free). Comply with any government data restrictions.

SAMPLE TECHNICAL STACK (practical)

  • Data ingest/prep: Google Earth Engine (Python), rasterio, GDAL, geopandas.

  • Model training: PyTorch, torchvision, albumentations.

  • Tabular models: scikit-learn, xgboost.

  • Serving: FastAPI + uvicorn, containerized with Docker; use AWS/GCP/Azure for scale.

  • DB: PostGIS for geospatial queries, optionally Redis for caching.

  • Monitoring: Prometheus + Grafana, plus periodic re-labeling workflow.

EXAMPLE: minimal Python sketch for extracting a patch (pseudocode)

python
import rasterio
from rasterio.windows import Window
import numpy as np
def extract_patch(raster_path, lon, lat, patch_size_m=256):
    # assume raster is in EPSG:3857 or convert coordinates beforehand
    with rasterio.open(raster_path) as src:
        px, py = src.index(lon, lat)      # pixel coords
        half = patch_size_m // src.res[0] # approximate pixels
        window = Window(px-half, py-half, 2*half, 2*half)
        patch = src.read(window=window)   # shape: (bands, H, W)
    return np.transpose(patch, (1,2,0))   # H,W,B

(you‚Äôll adapt for CRS/resolution; use GEE to avoid local downloads if needed)

README.md

# Landuse Point Classifier

Predict land-use class (e.g., residential, agriculture, forest, water, industrial, commercial, barren, transportation) for a given lat/lon in India.

## Quick start
1. Create a Python environment and install requirements:

```bash
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate
pip install -r requirements.txt

  1. Authenticate Google Earth Engine (required for data/gee_extract.py):

pip install earthengine-api
earthengine authenticate

  1. Run data/gee_extract.py to export Sentinel-2 patches for sample points (edit file to point to your CSV of points).

  2. Run python src/train.py to train a baseline model (creates model.pt).

  3. Start the API server:

python inference/serve.py --model-path model.pt

Files

See data/ for ingestion and preprocessing, src/ for model and training, and inference/ for serving.

## requirements.txt

numpy pandas geopandas rasterio earthengine-api torch torchvision scikit-learn xgboost fastapi uvicorn tqdm opencv-python matplotlib


```python
# data/gee_extract.py
# Usage: edit SAMPLE_POINTS_CSV to point at a CSV with columns: id,lat,lon,label(optional)
# This script uses the Earth Engine Python API to create and download 256m Sentinel-2 patches centered at points.

import ee
import os
import csv
import json
from pathlib import Path

# Edit these
SAMPLE_POINTS_CSV = 'examples/sample_points.csv'
OUT_DIR = 'data/patches'
PATCH_SIZE_M = 256 # patch side length in meters
BANDS = ['B4', 'B3', 'B2', 'B8'] # R,G,B,NIR
COMPOSITE_START = '2021-01-01'
COMPOSITE_END = '2021-12-31'

Path(OUT_DIR).mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

# Initialize EE
ee.Initialize()

def get_patch_image(lon, lat):
pt = ee.Geometry.Point([float(lon), float(lat)])
s2 = ee.ImageCollection('COPERNICUS/S2_SR') \
.filterBounds(pt) \
.filterDate(COMPOSITE_START, COMPOSITE_END) \
.filter(ee.Filter.lt('CLOUDY_PIXEL_PERCENTAGE', 40))
# median composite
img = s2.median().select(BANDS)
# rename bands to short names
img = img.rename(BANDS)
scale = 10
half = PATCH_SIZE_M / 2
region = pt.buffer(half).bounds().getInfo()['coordinates']
return img, region


def download_patch(lon, lat, out_path):
img, region = get_patch_image(lon, lat)
# request a small PNG or GeoTIFF export; here we export as GeoTIFF to Drive is avoided ‚Äî we use getThumb URL
url = img.getThumbURL({'region': region, 'dimensions': 256, 'format': 'geoTIFF'})
# Earth Engine courtesy: direct download via URL
import requests
r = requests.get(url)
if r.status_code == 200:
with open(out_path, 'wb') as f:
f.write(r.content)
return True
return False


def main():
with open(SAMPLE_POINTS_CSV) as f:
reader = csv.DictReader(f)
for row in reader:
pid = row.get('id') or f"p_{row['lat']}_{row['lon']}"
out_file = os.path.join(OUT_DIR, f"{pid}.tif")
if os.path.exists(out_file):
print('exists', out_file)
continue
ok = download_patch(row['lon'], row['lat'], out_file)
print(pid, 'ok' if ok else 'fail')

if __name__ == '__main__':
main()

Notes: earthengine getThumbURL has limitations. For large-scale export use ee.batch.Export.image.toDrive or Google Cloud. This script is intended for a small pilot and demonstration.

data/compute_indices.py

# compute NDVI, NDWI, NDBI from a 4-band array (R,G,B,NIR)
import numpy as np

def compute_indices(img):
# img: numpy array shape (H,W,4) with bands [R,G,B,NIR]
R = img[...,0].astype(np.float32)
G = img[...,1].astype(np.float32)
B = img[...,2].astype(np.float32)
NIR = img[...,3].astype(np.float32)
eps = 1e-6
ndvi = (NIR - R) / (NIR + R + eps)
ndwi = (G - NIR) / (G + NIR + eps)
ndbi = (NIR - SW := (img[...,3] - img[...,2])) / (NIR + SW + eps) # rough ndbi proxy
return np.stack([ndvi, ndwi, ndbi], axis=-1)

data/prepare_patches.py

# data/prepare_patches.py
# Reads GeoTIFF patches created by gee_extract.py, computes indices and saves numpy arrays + label file

import rasterio
import numpy as np
import os
from pathlib import Path
from tqdm import tqdm

IN_DIR = 'data/patches'
OUT_DIR = 'data/np_patches'
Path(OUT_DIR).mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

LABELS_CSV = 'examples/sample_points.csv' # must contain id,label

import csv
id_to_label = {}
with open(LABELS_CSV) as f:
for r in csv.DictReader(f):
if 'label' in r and r['label']:
id_to_label[r['id']] = r['label']

for fname in tqdm(os.listdir(IN_DIR)):
if not fname.endswith('.tif'):
continue
pid = Path(fname).stem
path = os.path.join(IN_DIR, fname)
try:
with rasterio.open(path) as src:
arr = src.read() # shape (bands, H, W)
# reorder to H,W,B and normalize
arr = np.transpose(arr, (1,2,0)).astype(np.float32)
# simple min-max normalization per band
for b in range(arr.shape[2]):
mn, mx = np.nanmin(arr[:,:,b]), np.nanmax(arr[:,:,b])
if mx - mn > 0:
arr[:,:,b] = (arr[:,:,b] - mn) / (mx - mn)
# compute indices (naive) - keep only bands present
# here assume 4 bands R,G,B,NIR
if arr.shape[2] >= 4:
from compute_indices import compute_indices
inds = compute_indices(arr[..., :4])
out = np.concatenate([arr[..., :4], inds], axis=-1)
else:
out = arr
np.save(os.path.join(OUT_DIR, pid + '.npy'), out)
# optionally save label
if pid in id_to_label:
with open(os.path.join(OUT_DIR, 'labels.csv'), 'a') as lf:
lf.write(f"{pid},{id_to_label[pid]}\n")
except Exception as e:
print('err', pid, e)

src/dataset.py

# src/dataset.py
import os
import numpy as np
from torch.utils.data import Dataset
from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

class PatchDataset(Dataset):
def __init__(self, np_dir, labels_csv=None, transform=None):
self.np_dir = np_dir
self.files = [f for f in os.listdir(np_dir) if f.endswith('.npy')]
self.transform = transform
self.labels = None
if labels_csv and os.path.exists(labels_csv):
import csv
id_to_label = {}
with open(labels_csv) as f:
for r in csv.reader(f):
pid, lab = r
id_to_label[pid] = lab
self.labels = id_to_label
self.le = LabelEncoder()
self.le.fit(list(set(id_to_label.values())))

def __len__(self):
return len(self.files)

def __getitem__(self, idx):
fn = self.files[idx]
pid = os.path.splitext(fn)[0]
arr = np.load(os.path.join(self.np_dir, fn)) # H,W,C
# transpose to C,H,W for pytorch
x = arr.transpose((2,0,1)).astype('float32')
y = -1
if self.labels and pid in self.labels:
y = int(self.le.transform([self.labels[pid]])[0])
if self.transform:
x = self.transform(x)
return x, y, pid

src/model.py

# src/model.py
import torch
import torch.nn as nn
import torchvision.models as models

class ResNetSmall(nn.Module):
def __init__(self, in_channels=7, num_classes=8):
super().__init__()
# load a pretrained resnet18 and adapt first conv
self.backbone = models.resnet18(pretrained=True)
# replace first conv to accept in_channels
old_conv = self.backbone.conv1
self.backbone.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels, old_conv.out_channels, kernel_size=old_conv.kernel_size, stride=old_conv.stride, padding=old_conv.padding, bias=False)
# if in_channels !=3, initialize weights
if in_channels != 3:
with torch.no_grad():
self.backbone.conv1.weight[:, :3, :, :] = old_conv.weight
if in_channels > 3:
for i in range(3, in_channels):
self.backbone.conv1.weight[:, i:i+1, :, :].copy_(old_conv.weight[:, :1, :, :])
self.backbone.fc = nn.Linear(self.backbone.fc.in_features, num_classes)

def forward(self, x):
return self.backbone(x)

src/train.py

# src/train.py
import os
import torch
from torch.utils.data import DataLoader
import torch.nn.functional as F
from torch import optim
from src.dataset import PatchDataset
from src.model import ResNetSmall

NP_DIR = 'data/np_patches'
LABELS_CSV = 'data/np_patches/labels.csv'
MODEL_OUT = 'model.pt'
BATCH_SIZE = 16
EPOCHS = 8
LR = 1e-4
DEVICE = 'cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu'


def collate_fn(batch):
xs = [b[0] for b in batch]
ys = [b[1] for b in batch]
import numpy as np
xs = torch.tensor(np.stack(xs)).float()
ys = torch.tensor(ys).long()
return xs, ys


def train():
ds = PatchDataset(NP_DIR, labels_csv=LABELS_CSV)
num_classes = len(ds.le.classes_)
dl = DataLoader(ds, batch_size=BATCH_SIZE, shuffle=True, collate_fn=collate_fn)
# infer channels from first sample
sample = np.load(os.path.join(NP_DIR, ds.files[0]))
in_ch = sample.shape[2]
model = ResNetSmall(in_channels=in_ch, num_classes=num_classes).to(DEVICE)
opt = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=LR)
for epoch in range(EPOCHS):
model.train()
total_loss = 0.0
for x, y in dl:
x = x.to(DEVICE)
y = y.to(DEVICE)
logits = model(x)
loss = F.cross_entropy(logits, y)
opt.zero_grad()
loss.backward()
opt.step()
total_loss += loss.item() * x.size(0)
print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{EPOCHS} loss={total_loss/len(ds):.4f}")
torch.save({'model_st

# Charan Vijayan ‚Äî Portfolio

Built with Vite + React + Tailwind. Place `src/App.jsx` (created in canvas) as the main component.

## Local dev
1. npm install
2. npm run dev

## Build & publish (GitHub Pages)
1. npm run build
2. Commit `docs/` to repo root (GitHub Pages will serve it) or use the Actions workflow included to deploy automatically.

  1. Optional .prettierrc (recommended)

json

  1. GitHub Actions workflow for automatic deploy to GitHub Pages: create .github/workflows/deploy.yml

yaml
name: Deploy to GitHub Pages
on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  build-and-deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    steps:
      - name: Checkout
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Setup Node
        uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with:
          node-version: '20'

      - name: Install dependencies
        run: npm ci

      - name: Build
        run: npm run build

      - name: Deploy to pages
        uses: actions/configure-pages@v4

      - name: Upload artifact
        uses: actions/upload-pages-artifact@v1
        with:
          path: ./docs

      - name: Publish
        uses: actions/deploy-pages@v1

This workflow builds the site into docs/ and uses GitHub Pages (Pages must be enabled to serve from gh-pages/docs via repo settings ‚Äî Actions will publish automatically).

Commands to create repository locally and push to GitHub

Run these in your terminal (replace placeholders):

bash
# prepare local project
mkdir charan-portfolio
cd charan-portfolio
# create files as above (or copy them in)
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit: Vite + React + Tailwind portfolio"

# create remote repo (replace <YOUR_GITHUB> and repo name)
gh repo create your-username/charan-portfolio --public --source=. --remote=origin --push
# if you don't have gh CLI, create repo on github.com then:
# git remote add origin https://github.com/your-username/charan-portfolio.git
# git push -u origin main

If gh repo create pushes to main branch, the GitHub Actions workflow will run on push and publish the site.

Minimal Setup checklist (ordered, fastest path)

  1. Create project folder, add the files above.

  2. Copy src/App.jsx from the canvas into src/App.jsx.

  3. Run:

    bash
    npm install
npm run dev

    Verify locally at http://localhost:5173.

  4. Commit and push to GitHub main.

  5. Wait for Actions to finish ‚Äî site will be served from repository Pages (check repo's Pages settings if needed).

Notes, caveats, and quick optimizations

  • This is efficient: Vite build ‚Üí static docs/ dir ‚Üí GitHub Pages. No server or Docker required.

  • If you prefer immediate domain + SSL, set repo GitHub Pages or use Netlify/Vercel (drag-and-drop or one-click deploy).

Troubleshooting (common issues & fixes)

  • Action fails with npm ci error: check package.json formatting and run npm install locally to ensure no errors.

  • Pages shows 404: open Settings ‚Üí Pages and ensure branch is gh-pages or main with folder docs. With Actions above, Pages should be configured automatically; if not, set Branch: main and Folder: /docs.

  • Site not updating: Push new commits to main ‚Äî Actions will rebuild and republish.

  • No main branch: ensure you ran git branch -M main before pushing.
